Inflation in Europe rises due to food prices
The accelerating inflation in the euro area is mainly due to the steady rise in food prices.
In November, price growth in 13 eurozone countries was higher than expected, with an annual inflation of 3.1% recorded in October after 2.6%, the Luxembourg Statistical Office of the Union said.
The official forecast was only 3 percent, Bloomberg.
Unlike the U.S., British and Canadian issuing banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) did not lower its base interest rate, saying that a reduction, along with rising commodity prices and falling unemployment, would lead to an inflationary spiral.
The ECB wants to keep inflation below 2% but close to it.
According to one of the analysts, the ECB is in an absurd situation: it must “distract” inflation so that it will not have to do anything about it later.
In Germany, the November inflation rate of 3.3 percent represents a fifteen-year record; in Spain it rose from 3.6 percent to 4.1 percent.
Inflation in the eurozone has risen due to rising food and energy prices.
Terminal wheat prices rose by 88 percent, and the price of soybean has reached its highest since 1973.
Similarly, in 2007 it was necessary to pay significantly more for edible oil and dairy products.
Oil prices on the world markets rose 52 percent this year and last month a barrel of black gold already cost $100.
According to the ECB, inflation will jump from 2.1 percent in 2008 to 2.5 percent this year, but will drop to 1.9 percent in 2009.
According to analysts, the level of 12-month inflation in the next 3-4 months will remain approximately at 3 percent, but its average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to cut interest rates twice in 2008.
