In many places, disinfectants are used.
More than a thousand cases of infection have been in hospitals this year, mainly due to improper use of antibiotics.
Hygienic conditions in hospitals, overcrowding of beds, overcrowding of personnel do not help stop the infection, the primary of the National Epidemiological Center said.
In many places, disinfectants are also saved.
Recently, MRSA infection was diagnosed at the traumatological department of St. John's Hospital.
Antibiotic-resistant bacteria have been discovered in a man who got to the hospital after a serious car accident.
The patient was isolated.
A similar infection occurred in the same place at the beginning of the year.
The patient injured in a serious car accident was released home, but soon afterwards he had to return with an MRSA infection and because of the bacteria found in his body, one important operation could not have been performed.
As of December 10 this year, 1,094 hospital infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens have been to the National System of Nesocomialis Surveillance, said Karolina Böröcz, primary of the National Epidemiological Center.
This means that so many infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens have been confidently recorded in hospitals, others are not known.
Nearly two-thirds (683) of infections were caused by MRSA, or methicillin-oxacillin-resistant gold staphylococcus.
Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria is carried by one-third of people in the nose without causing disease.
Infections caused by SA (e.g. cervical inflammation, tonsillitis, skin infections, morning infections) respond well to antibiotics and can be treated well.
However, if antibiotics are administered in excessive or inappropriate amounts, a bacterium that responds well to antibiotics will develop into a bacterium that is very resistant to antibiotics and spreads rapidly in inappropriate hospital conditions.
Especially in the case of temporary or permanent malfunction of the immune system in patients with a weakened body, low body weight or in patients in years can cause serious hospital infections, such as morning infection or blood poisoning - sepsis.
According to the top doctor of St. John's Hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infection, similar infections are a daily practice in hospitals.
“Infection should not be confused with an epidemic, MRSA is not just there,” Tibor Nyulasi said, “where the presence of a disease-causing agent is not investigated.”
Resists antibiotics
“We isolate these patients, the care staff treats them in rubber gloves and in a mask and we have the necessary antibiotics to treat them,” Nyulasi said.
Patients who are admitted to the hospital are first examined to see if MRSA is present in their bodies, but the infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling is not in fashion.
The overwhelming majority of hospital infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but the current conditions and conditions in home hospitals are not favourable for the prevention of the emergence and spread of multiresistant disease agents, says Karolina Böröczová.
As this infection occurs symptomatically in hospitals and homes for the elderly, hospitals should check patients and immediately isolate MRSA carriers.
However, microbiological sampling is not in fashion in Hungarian hospitals.
The National Health Insurance Fund does not fund these tests.
Most cases are revealed if the patient suffers from a noticeable MRSA infection, the primary of the epidemiological center said.
The European Union has strict recommendations for appropriate treatment with antibiotics in the field of human medicine and there are also domestic guidelines for the treatment of individual infections, diseases.
Antibiotic therapy should be targeted, i.e. microbiological examinations should be carried out to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not comply with this in all cases.
Microbiological sampling is even more rare in primary and ambulatory treatment of patients, Karolina Böröcz said.
Saving on disinfectants
According to scientific evidence, MRSA is spread among patients most often through medical staff.
Therefore, handwashing and the use of gloves and masks play a very important role, but there are also serious deficiencies in hospitals.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection and touch, but it is not always possible to isolate infected patients in the conditions of home hospitals.
The rooms, on the other hand, are often crowded, the beds are often very close to each other, although from an epidemiological point of view, patients should be at least 1.5 meters away from each other.
As Karolina Böröcz pointed out, unfortunately, we can also encounter the fact that in hospitals that are in a disadvantaged material situation, they are saving on disinfectants, there are few caregivers and many patients, thereby increasing the chance of infection.
According to Karolina Böröcz, where necessary protective measures are observed, similar infections are proved to be fewer or the further spread of the pathogen can be stopped.
Government Programme Against MRSA
Treatment of MRSA infection is an enormous cost for health insurance companies, so it is being fought everywhere.
For example, in England, the government has drafted a program for preventing MRSA and reducing its incidence.
As it seems, the program is successful, according to published data, MRSA infections in England show a declining trend.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) ranks prevention of multi-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and hospital infections caused by these pathogens as its priorities.
