EUR 400 million for infrastructure
The agreement on three loan frameworks worth €400 million to support education, transport and environmental infrastructure as well as energy was signed on Friday in Budapest by Finance Minister János Veres and Marta Gajecka, Vice President of the European Investment Bank (EIB).
The European Investment Bank (EIB) approved in 2006 a framework of €300 million for Hungary’s budget financing of projects in the field of transport and the environment, implemented with the support of the Cohesion Fund, with the parties already concluding a loan agreement for the amount of €100 million, now signed the agreement concerns the use of the remaining €200 million.
A loan agreement of €150 million is also available for budget financing of projects related to education.
The EIB has approved a total of €300 million for Hungary for this purpose, the remaining €150 million may be used later, with the extension of the loan agreement.
In the field of innovation, the parties signed a contract for 50 million euros, which the budget will be used primarily for the research and development project of the University of Debrecen.
There was also a discussion on the fourth route.
The parties agreed that after Hungary has agreed with the EU on the details of the subway financing, it will return to whether and how the original contract should be modified.
This could happen in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has funded a total of 113 projects in Hungary in the amount of EUR 8.4 billion.
Interest on loans granted by the EIB with an eight-year waiting period and without commitment commission shall be bound by the EURIBOR rate.
Bulgaria is the paradise of the European Union
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is overwhelming - the attention of all Europe is turning to the previously somewhat neglected Balkan country.
What, where and who is buying on the cheapest yet fastest rising EU market?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
The most sought-after Eastern European destination for real estate purchases is now undoubtedly Bulgaria with its cheap ski apartments and seaside houses.
Of the mountains are most in the course of the areas of Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitoša, on the sea coast then Albena, Golden Sands, Sunny Coast, ancient cities of Sozopol and Nesebar, but more and more people are also looking for properties around Kavarna and Balčik.
According to analysts from Re/Max Bulgaria, sooner or later the interest of investors will also be aroused by the central part of the country - for example, Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna - and more and more interested people are also shopping in the vicinity of the expansively cheap city of Ruse.
Also, the capital city of Sofia is a promise of tempting options, business and office spaces promise the highest return.
Bulgaria is on its best path to becoming one of the most attractive golf havens in Europe, becoming a sought-after destination in addition to the summer and winter seasons for two more seasons.
Forecasting investors are already buying in large, for example, in the area of Banska.
According to analysts, real estate buyers in Bulgaria are trying to change their lives and lifestyle at the same time.
Most customers come from England, but there are also buyers from France, Belgium, Spain and increasingly also from Romania.
There are also Maltese and Cypriot investors here, and there are traditionally many Russian customers near the Black Sea and ski resorts.
Foreign buyers are divided into three groups, says Georgy Jankov, regional director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
Settlers buy either renovated properties worth 50-100 thousand euros, or lost old houses for 5-15 thousand euros, which they then renovate.
They require good availability and communication opportunities, the proximity of a big city, shops and, as a rule, a local doctor is important for them.
The second category are chat buyers (Bulgaria ranked among the top 10 German holiday destinations in December).
The third group consists of commercial investors who buy in the hope of rising value in the medium or long term.
The price of real estate in the capital is continuous, as demand is increasing.
Bulgaria has the lowest real estate prices in the European Union, but has grown by 21% annually over the past five years.
The rise in real estate prices significantly exceeds the growth in wages.
Fodor and the Hungarian six percent
According to the information of the Minister of the Environment and Water Management Gabor Fodor, the meetings of experts will be concluded on Tuesday, and after Wednesday's official opening, the international conference on the climate regime after 2012 will continue with ministerial talks.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries are negotiating the Bali Roadmap, which addresses efforts following the emissions reduction period defined by the Kyoto Protocol until 2012.
There is a fierce debate between developed and developing countries.
The United States has also announced that it is not now willing to negotiate precise figures, although it is inclined to agree to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40 percent by 2020 compared to 1990.
Another big question at the conference is whether developed countries will, in addition to reducing emissions, also provide both material and technological assistance to countries that are dependent on it.
The agreement also includes subsidies for developing countries.
The subsidy fund, established by the Kyoto Protocol, will be run by a 16-member management board, probably within the framework of the United Nations World Environment Programme (GEF) - we can read in the journal Piac és Profit.
Hungarian 6%
Environment and Water Minister Gábor Fodor, on behalf of Hungary, supports the EU’s efforts to maintain its leadership in global climate protection efforts and to contribute to a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister said the EU is committed to reducing greenhouse gas emissions by 20 percent by 2020 compared to 1990 levels, regardless of the success of the adoption of the "deal after 2012", and is ready to commit to a reduction of up to 30 percent if other developed regions of the world, respectively, are willing to accept responsibilities and commitments corresponding to their capabilities.
Gábor Fodor pointed out that the countries that joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 blamed themselves for a reduction target of 5.2 percent, with the then 15 EU member states committing to 8 percent.
The commitment of Hungary is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6 percent compared to 1985-87, which our country will fulfill.
In Bali, a long-term international agreement on climate change policy needs to be reached within two years, otherwise its entry into force would be delayed until 2012. In such a case, a new emission reduction scheme would not immediately be imposed on the Kyoto Protocol’s commitments to reduce emissions, which the International Panel on Climate Change (IPCC), the recipient of the Nobel Peace Prize, also pointed out in its latest report.
This would lead to a delay in emissions reduction and an inevitable rise in average Earth temperature by more than 2 degrees Celsius, which would have extremely serious and irreversible consequences, according to the scientists.
British army recruits on YouTube
British military units are publishing on a video-sharing server recordings of actions in Iraq and Afghanistan, by which they popularize themselves.
First, the British Air Force (RAF) liked YouTube: special forces operating in Afghanistan have been uploading videos of actions against the Taliban here since March 2006, the BBC.
The recordings, taken by a miniature camera attached to the helmet, are monitored by the Air Force Command in charge of combat operations in the Kandahar area and then sent further to London, where they are transmitted to the Internet.
The political message is inevitable.
In this form, 139 records of British Air Force soldiers have been posted on the Internet, and more than 75,000 people have viewed their channel.
The British Ministry of Defense registered in the spring of 2007 as “defenceheadquarters” and publishes recordings of actions in Iraq and Afghanistan, while the British Foreign Office (Commonwealth Office) and International Peacekeeping Forces in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channels.
Deployment in Afghanistan
The Air Force has released videos according to its original intention for recruitment purposes and, according to the Defense Ministry, are good even to familiarize the general public with the real goal of military presence abroad.
“Propaganda published in this form compared to traditional television recruitment advertisements costs almost nothing,” said Gordon Mackenzie, a defense expert at the BBC, “but it necessarily carries a certain political message as it confirms the legitimacy of military actions decided by the government in a special form.”
The Americans played.
The army is concerned that, in addition to carefully edited, censored recordings, amateur videos are also sent to the server, capturing, for example, the death of soldiers: in somewhat hypocritical, "official" promotional films, officers speak about losses, but the bloody image of the fight is not shown.
Many videos of combat sites in Iraq and Afghanistan have already been posted on the Internet, but the British army has only been able to find them now.
Americans do the recruitment a little differently – using a shooting game called America’s Army, which is free to download and in which the player can get straight into the skin of the soldiers through a more or less loyal simulation.
