Going to a massive strike
The League and the National Union of Workers’ Councils (MOSZ) will set up a strike commission on Friday to coordinate Monday’s unlimited strike.
A protest public assembly will be held on Saturday, on Monday - on the day of the final vote on the Health Insurance Act - work will be stopped.
The action will cause serious traffic disruptions, as railway traffic will be almost completely stopped and employees of the Budapest Transport Enterprise (BKV) will also strike by 13 o'clock.
On Friday afternoon, the League association, together with the National Union of Workers’ Councils, will present the details of the jointly organised Monday strike.
A strike commission will also be formed, which will coordinate the action on Monday.
A protest public assembly will take place on Saturday, and since Monday, unions joining the strike will stop work indefinitely unless an agreement is reached with the government.
This means that no deadline has been set for the end of the strike, which will begin on the day of the parliamentary vote on the Health Insurance Act.
If the Parliament does not finally pass the health insurance law, the unions will immediately withdraw the call for a strike.
However, if the legislation is voted out, the strike committees will meet and decide on the further procedure.
According to the agenda of the Parliament’s meeting on Monday, it is also possible that the Health Insurance Act will be voted only late in the evening or at night.
Due to the strike starting on Monday, it is possible to count on serious traffic disruptions: on the railway, work will be stopped indefinitely, in the morning, part of Budapest's public transportation and more than half of Volán companies can stop.
At the same time, half of the road will be closed in many parts of the country.
Numerous unions and civil society organizations have joined the strike call, whose list is constantly updated on the League’s website.
Some organizations have announced an indefinite strike, while others have declared a temporary shutdown.
Until Thursday afternoon, the Hungarian State Railways (MÁV) and the Independent Trade Union of Railway Workers (VDSZSZ) were unable to agree on sufficient services, while the beginning of the Christmas holidays more and more people travel by rail.
According to previous reports, the BKV will strike from the start of operation until 13 o’clock, from 7 to 9 o’clock in the morning at the Budapest Airport, a four-hour strike is organised by the Labor Unions of Workers in the Energy Industry LIGA, and the Labor Union of Pedagogues and the Democratic Trade Union of Pedagogues has called for a 2- and 2-8-hour stop of work.
The Hungarian Union of Physicians will strike alternately across the country, while the Democratic Trade Union of Health and Social Workers (EDDSZ), part of the Cooperative Forum of Trade Unions (SZEF), is holding a two-hour warning strike.
The most important of the four demands formulated by the League is that the government withdraw the draft health insurance reform and submit a new concept for public discussion.
The second requirement is that the new method of calculating pensions in force from next year will be introduced gradually.
Thirdly, the possibility of inclusion in the system of early retirement for the respective occupational sectors should be ensured before 2010.
The fourth reason for the action is that the Independent Trade Union of Railway Workers (VDSZSZ), which belongs to the League trade union, does not accept the offer of the Ministry of Economy and Transport regarding railway branches, and expects a different offer.
Political Capital: Hungarian Guard Increases Country Risk
The activity of the Hungarian Guard, established with the support of the Jobbik Magyarországért movement in August this year, according to the Risk Analysis Division of the Political Capital Institute has increased the political risk of Hungary and the region in several respects.
The company’s “warning on risks” states that in connection with the activities of the Hungarian Guard, the greatest political risk is that “the aggravation of the already existing ethnic tensions between the Roma and non-Roma population of Hungary can lead to violent ethnic clashes in a short time.”
The main reason is that the Hungarian Guard’s political strategy is likely aimed at provoking such an action, adds the research institute.
As he writes, all this can be explained by one of the greatest negligences of Hungarian political leaders: “The public discussion on the Roma question was left by the officials of public life to representatives of radical and extremist political groups, who could build a political strategy on the Roma-Hungarian contradiction.”
This deepens the problem, makes normal dialogue impossible, strengthens extremists and increases the likelihood of violent conflict.
In addition, the activities of the Hungarian Guard, according to the research institute, influenced by the great attention of domestic and foreign media, “have largely damaged the image of Hungary abroad, especially as regards the belief in the stability of the country and its democratic maturity”.
Part of the reorganization of the Hungarian radical and ultra-right groups, which since the fall of 2006 has been receiving increasing publicity and popularity, is that in Hungary since the summer of 2007 several organizations have been formed, which call themselves associations of "national defense".
“The common feature of these groups is that they define themselves as civil associations, while openly proclaiming – even armed – the readiness of their members to perform defensive tasks (in the event of natural disasters, attacks on the homeland, disruption of order), plus pointing to the inability of the police, the army, or the state,” he adds.
He further notes: all this is happening in a way that seeks to wrap all kinds of political efforts built on society’s resistance to politics and parties into civilian clothes.
Therefore, the emphasis on civility and the form of the association in the case of these groups serves not only to avoid the legal obstacles of judicial registration, but is also a political strategy.
According to the analysis, the activity of the Hungarian Guard is a factor increasing the risk also in terms of neighbourly relations.
In recent months, the Hungarian Guard has been pointed out in several neighboring countries as a potential source of danger, and the ultranacionalist political leaders of some neighboring countries have appealed to the formation of the Hungarian Guard to excuse their own anti-Hungary policy.
All this could have an impact on the political stability of the region,” he added.
According to the research institute, the emergence of the Hungarian Guard in Central and Eastern Europe is not a rare phenomenon, so the political risks for the region as a whole have increased.
The activity of the Hungarian Guard is similar, for example, to the activities of the Bulgarian National Guard, the creation of which was announced in August 2007 by the far-right Bulgarian National Union (BNU).
In the background of the formation of the Bulgarian Guard, there are massive Roma riots that erupted in one of the Sofia districts (Krasna Poljana).
This was used by the BNU to establish the Guard, stating that the organization’s goal is “national defense.”
In the past 17 years there has been a “Gypsy terror” in Bulgaria, but the state has remained inactive and indifferent, according to the Political Capital Institute.
He added that the initiative sparked a fierce debate among the Bulgarian public.
The increased risk of ethnic clashes is signaled by the announcement by some Bulgarian Roma organizations that they will set up their own guard in the sign of resistance.
