Banks want to solve the crisis
The Federal Reserve Bank of the United States, the European Central Bank and the central banks of Britain, Switzerland and Canada have decided to jointly tackle the financial market crisis.
More than $100 billion will be raised through auctions.
In these auctions, banks auction the interest rate at which they are willing to borrow money.
For example, the U.S. Federal Reserve will send $40 billion to auction, and another $24 billion will be available to the European and Swiss central banks.
This is the first time since the September 11 attacks that national central banks have agreed on such a coordinated approach to prevent or mitigate the consequences of the financial crisis.
“This move is meant to address the biggest difficulties of the economy, i.e. the growing shortage of free capital that banks could borrow,” Bernard Baumohl of the consultancy Economic Outlook Group wrote in his report to clients.
“Coordinated action by central banks has reduced the likelihood of a recession in the United States from 65 percent to 50 percent,” Baumohl added in his report.
Banks have already lost $60 billion due to unpaid loans, mainly in the United States.
Analysts expect additional billions of dollars.
“Central banks need to be really concerned about what might be next when they decide to take this step,” said ABN chief economist Amro Kieran Davies.
“It looks like the situation is really bad,” he added.
Central banks are concerned that if banks themselves have difficult access to loans, they will lend to their customers as well.
This would reduce consumption and send the U.S. economy into a recession with potential impacts on global economic growth.
The central banks made this decision after failing to reduce the so-called LIBOR, the London interbank rate used for borrowing money on the interbank market.
This meant that banks were still concerned about borrowing money from each other, despite the central banks of the United States, Canada and Britain having lowered their interest rates several times during the autumn.
“It will have the same effect as another drop in interest rates,” Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting told Reuters.
Some analysts do not believe that the central bank’s move will help fuel the crisis because it does not solve the underlying problem, and that is the fall of the U.S. real estate market.
