Who will succeed Putin in the presidency?
The official newspaper announced the date of the first round of the presidential election, March 2, 2008; candidates can present themselves to the public until December 23.
Vladimir Putin, who was elected in 2000 and re-elected in 2004, is unable to run for a third term in a row.
No followers appear.
What role will Putin play after March?
Will he be prime minister?
Or the leader of the parliamentary majority and all-powerful United Russia party, which will choose a government and a president?
Either way, the outgoing ruling power will win the whole line in parliamentary as well as in presidential elections.
It is tradition.
“The Russians have the mentality of homo sovietica, they don’t feel like they are masters of their fate,” says Lev Gudkov, a sociologist and director of the independent center Levada.
The historian Nikolai Kopossov of the State University of St. Petersburg notes a more distant context in time: the civil society, in this country Christianized five centuries after Europe, has been delayed; this glorious common spirit has delayed the formation of individualism.
After the liberal reforms of the 1990s, "Putin followed a paternalistic model of the state, perfectly accepted by the population, and this new paternalism was not accompanied by terror, but by some economic prosperity," says Maria Lipman of the Carnegie Foundation.
The Russians today “voluntarily give up their personal responsibility” which they demonstrated shortly after the collapse of the USSR.
“Why think?”
This phenomenon affects all layers of society, including the business world.
Even the official elite intends to maintain the status quo: 65 governors (out of a total of 85 heads of Russian regions) rule the local candidates of United Russia.
New freedoms taken from the West are often, as in the 1990s, synonymous with chaos.
The public preferred stability.
Also, in the name of stability, the Russians will not vote for extremists.
The conclusion of Tamara Cherednichenko, a fifty-four-year-old professor: "Why to think?
Those who are in power are not so bad, so why change them?”
loaded memory
After more than sixty years in the confidential regime, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which depict the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are being opened to the public.
47 million archival documents stored over a length of 27 km in Bad Arolsen (Hesse) were until then accessible only for "humanitarian" purposes, that is, individually and namely, at the request of the former victim or its authorized persons.
In May, eleven countries, including Germany, France, Israel and the United States, agreed to open the archives to scientists and historians.
Since the process of ratification of this agreement by all countries is over, the opening came into effect yesterday.
Sensitive Information
The free access of historians to Bad Arolsen will allow to examine “especially the movements of prisoners, the population of camps and the health status of forced laborers,” explains Reto Meistern, director of these archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several states, including Germany, opposed the disclosure of these named documents to the public, due to the sensitive nature of some information.
What is the presumption of homosexuality or mental disability of some victims of deportation?
The registers of concentration camps or arrest warrants drawn up by the Gestapo were collected after the war for the practical purpose of finding the deported or forced labor of civilians subjected, bringing them evidence of their internment in order to open the way for their compensation.
Even today, more than 300 permanent employees in Bad Arolsen deal with tens of thousands of individual applications.
However, for part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen represents only a limited benefit.
"Nothing fundamentally new can be expected from these documents," said Wolfgang Benz, director of the Center for the Study of Antisemitism at Technische Universität Berlin in 2006.
