Congress approves implementation of MiFID from 1 November
Parallel to parliamentary talks, which ended today with a congressional vote on the amendments incorporated by the Senate into the bill, the government has undergone a public hearing of the regulations developing the new law, with the aim of both entering into force before the end of the year.
Representatives of the various parties unanimously highlighted the efforts of MEPs and Senators to negotiate and agree on the best standard to guarantee investor protection and detailed regulation of the activities of entities necessary for the effective functioning of markets.
The MiFID Directive, which regulates the Securities Trading Act, envisages the modernization of financial markets and at the same time strengthens investor protection, improves the supervisory powers of the State Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and promotes cooperation between the various supervisory authorities of the European Union.
This new regulation will enable financial advisory services to be provided to both specialized firms and natural or legal persons and creates a new type of financial services companies (ESIS), financial advisory companies (AFIs) that join securities companies, securities brokers and portfolio managers.
In addition, the number of systems for carrying out transactions with financial instruments is being expanded by connecting multilateral trading systems and order internalization systems to regulated secondary markets, which will compete with current stock exchange brokers.
Furthermore, the law obliges companies providing investment services to disseminate on the market information on key aspects of their business profile, exposure to risk and methods of coping with risk, and requiresining a report of all operations carried out to facilitate supervision by CNMV.
During the negotiations in the Congressional Trade Commission, a number of adjustments were included, among which stands that securitised receivables should be regarded as a "complex" financial instrument given the high risk to the investor, which was demonstrated by what happened in the U.S. with high-risk mortgage debt (subprime).
Furthermore, the transposition of the Directive has been used to legalise the functions that may be held by undergraduates in the field of economics and business management 30 years after a royal decree in 1977 established the professional functions reserved for economists.
The Senate also included the creation of new professions in the financial sector, such as a broker who will work externally, will not require permission from CNMV and will be able to provide products trading and customer acquisition services for different investment firms at the same time.
