New gas dispute between Russia and Ukraine
Russia and Ukraine are currently facing a dispute over the price of natural gas, increasing the risk that Russian gas supplies to Western Europe may be affected.
Most of the Russian fuel exported to the European Union (EU) is conducted by pipeline through Ukraine, and any dispute between the two countries is closely monitored.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow raises gas prices to Ukraine, it will charge Russia higher transit fees.
The previous dispute between the two countries last year reduced supplies to EU countries.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow comes at a time when the Ukrainian government and the Russian state-owned gas monopoly Gazprom are trying to agree on how much Ukraine will have to pay for Russian gas in 2008.
Gazprom says it will have to charge Ukraine more because it has agreed to pay up to 50% more for gas it gets from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say this could mean that Ukraine will have to pay 40% more for its supplies from Gazprom.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit states during the negotiations," Ukrainian Economy Minister Anatoly Kinech told Reuters.
"The changes in gas prices should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the amount of transit fees (to Western Europe) through Ukraine."
The last major dispute between Moscow and Kiev caused Gazprom to cut supplies to Ukraine in January 2006.
This caused a drastic decline in exports to Western Europe, which sharply increased prices.
Russian gas accounts for one-fourth of all gas supplies to the European Union.
Russia has the largest gas reserves in the world, but much of it remains underused.
As a result, Gazprom supplements its own gas supplies with gas from Turkmenistan and other former Soviet Central Asian republics.
NHS 'must check out foreign employees'
The inspector said the Scottish NHS chambers must improve criminal records checks on non-European employees.
The recommendation from the president of the Supreme Audit Office, Robert Black, came after a foreign doctor working in Scotland was linked to the June attacks on Glasgow airport.
Mr Black is also concerned that the Scottish NHS has no precise idea of the amount of foreign staff it employs.
But his report highlighted that other key checks went well on a sample of five health authorities.
The president of the Supreme Audit Office was interested immediately after the June attacks on Glasgow airport in staff recruited from countries outside the European Economic Area.
Bilal Abdullah, a twenty-eight-year-old Iraqi doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after someone hit the door of the main terminal building with a jeep.
He was one of three doctors who appeared at the Central Criminal Court using a video bridge accused of linking to attempted bombings in the UK.
NHS chambers are expected to check foreign staff for qualifications, experience and authorization to work in the UK before hiring them.
Although the Scottish Health Commission uses Disclosure Scotland for criminal records checks, the agency has no authority to obtain such information outside the UK.
The report of the President of the Supreme Audit Office says, among other recommendations, that the commission should be guided by the guidelines of the Criminal Records Bureau, which helps employers with checks in several countries.
"Al we found that some of the staff records contained evidence of these checks, they are not carried out regularly," the report said.
Mr Black said the Scottish NHS is in much alignment with its own policy of pre-employment checks, but also added: “Our report highlights areas in which the system could be improved to ensure accurate information about the amount of foreign personnel is available.”
BMA Scotland Chairman Dr. Peter Terry said it was "very unlikely" that pre-employment checks would identify potential NHS employees who could commit a terrorist act in the future.
“The report suggests that current pre-employment checks at the Scottish NHS are working well and it’s not clear what additional value those comments will bring,” he said.
The Scottish health authorities said they currently have 1,161 foreign workers, the vast majority of whom are doctors and nurses.
However, the president of the Supreme Audit Office noted that these numbers will probably be higher also because the commission had a problem identifying personnel with a residence permit.
The survey also found that established control procedures at NHS authorities in the areas of Ayrshire and Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire and Lothian are largely implemented.
They included passport checks, work permits and qualifications.
The Scottish government is currently reviewing the policy and guidelines for pre-employment checks for foreign NHS workers.
Health Minister Nicola Sturgeon said: "I wanted to handle this job immediately after the terrorist attack on Glasgow airport."
She also added that the Scottish government, in agreement with the health committees, will consider the recommendations of this report and will ensure that best practices appear in updated guidelines for pre-employment checks of all staff – including foreign ones – that it plans to issue next month.
