Climate on Venus may be a glimpse into the future of Earth
Scientists have announced yesterday that Venus could once have been a pleasant place to live.
Data from an orbiting European station shows that the planet is even more similar to the swinging twin Earth than previously thought.
Venus is the nearest planetary neighbor to Earth.
These two worlds are roughly equal in size and orbiting on similar orbits, but Venus is a little closer to the Sun.
Scientists now believe that billions of years ago, conditions on Venus were similar to those on Earth and could have been habitable.
But the sluggish greenhouse effect caused by carbon dioxide, atmospheric erosion by solar radiation, and lower rotation rates have sent Venus on a completely different path of evolution.
Today, the planet is without water, the temperature on the surface is hot enough to melt lead and is devastated by storms and hurricane-powered winds.
The findings from the European Space Agency’s Venus Express spacecraft, which has studied the planet for one year, offer a blatant glimpse of how Earth could evolve in the event of catastrophic climate change.
Professor Fred Taylor of the Department of Physics at the University of Oxford and one of the leaders of the Venus Express mission said: "It's becoming increasingly clear why the climate on Venus is so different from that on Earth, even though the planets themselves are quite similar.
“Our new data allows us to compile a scenario in which Venus started just like Earth, even with a habitable environment, billions of years ago.”
