Labour Pain
Gordon Brown has again found a trap to fall into; his way out remains the same.
Although this is a common practice in British political scandals, this is not spicy.
No orders appear to have been sold, no bills in the Paris hotel have been mysteriously paid, no out-of-marriage fingers have been blotted.
But the barricaded Gordon Brown would go by without being discovered that some wealthy businessman for four years masqueraded contributions to the ruling Labour Party of £650,000 ($1.3 million) under the names of other people, and that the party did not report it.
Two months ago, when the prime minister avoided calling elections and insulted British intelligence by claiming that the decision was not influenced by surveys, there was hope to ensure a resilient and effective government.
Instead, as the increasingly funny liberal-democratic leader formulated, the once feared Mr. Brown changed from Stalin to Mr. Bean.
The unscrupulous rescue of the troubled bank Northern Rock showed weaknesses in management and poor judgment under fire.
The poorly thought out proposals to change the tax code have brought companies together against the government.
The loss of personal data of 25 million people revealed an unimaginable administrative barrier.
Three retired generals launched a rebellion in the House of Lords; they protested against cuts in military spending because they claimed that being a commander of the armed forces is part-time work.
Now there are many gifts from David Abraham; Peter Watt, Labour’s secretary-general (and their former guard of internal discipline), has already resigned.
Nothing of this means that Mr. Brown is inevitably heading towards his end.
Nevertheless, governments can reach a point of overthrow behind which they find governance difficult.
The people don’t trust politicians and don’t like them, but they mostly remove their mistrust when a new party takes over it.
When it seems clear that a prime minister is unlikely to do anything better, and may not even be in office for a long time, this shift is gone: the government becomes rotting, ministers begin to make briefings, the press is looking for bad news, and the government becomes unfocused and defensive.
In one sense, Mr. Brown’s position is complicated, as he cannot take the position of a new leader compared to other political leaders.
As much as he wanted to distance himself from Tony Blair, he was his first officer.
For example, problems with Northern Rock and the Treasury Office records are linked to the decisions Mr. Brown made as Minister of Finance.
And even though he wasn’t directly involved in Blair’s troubles, such as a long investigation into political party financing caused by “value for money,” voters can safely assume he was.
Still, Mr. Brown’s trouble is not as bad as it seems.
That is not as terrible as the conservatives do.
As for Mr. Bean, no one died or was deceived.
And the treatment, however painful it may be, is to provide what Mr. Brown’s Stalinist tendencies have always promised: a reliable, solid, and slightly brutal government.
The recent turmoil around political donations is a good example.
Garboid Mr. Abrahams, who compares his gifts to charity, says he did not want any publicity for his charity.
It may be true, but the decision was not on him.
The laws against the anonymity of big political donors are clear and exist for a simple reason: the public has the right to know who could buy access to those who rule the country.
Mr. Watt, who said he knew about Mr. Abraham’s action but didn’t know it was illegal, will surely be thoroughly questioned; likewise Jon Mendlesohn, the main Labour money-gatherer, who learned about the overwhelming donations in October.
But so far Mr. Brown is not in any way involved; there is nothing to suggest that he was aware of these tricks, even though most of the payments were made only after his arrival in June.
The Prime Minister has done half of the job.
He quickly condemned this violation of the law by his own party, but he diluted his determination by seeking a proven tool, a commission to investigate the matter, led by a retired bishop and a judge.
In this case, the lessons are not difficult.
If the law is violated, it is a matter of the police.
In addition, there are other things Mr. Brown has to do, such as find a permanent chairman of the independent Committee on Standards in Public Life, which hasn’t had one for six months, and move forward with a real reform of political party financing.
This would require Labour, who are in the narrow, to cooperate with the Conservatives and even give up their special financial relationship with the unions – bitter pills for a devout party like Mr. Brown.
But he should face a few simple facts.
Conservatives now have a decent lead in polls; he has two years to get the voters back; and the only way to win is with unquestionable integrity and high competence.
Card Shark
Does the mortgage crisis affect the U.S. credit card market?
When there is blood in the water, the backflies begin to stir around naturally.
Now that the U.S. real estate market is shrinking, predators have focused on the credit card market.
Analysts at Goldman Sachs say credit card losses could reach $99 billion if other consumer loans were infected by underlying mortgages.
Signs of tension are obvious.
There is an increase in the number of cases of failure to pay (with more than 30 days of payment delay) and depreciated accounts (accounts that the provider considers non-executable).
HSBC last month losses of $1.4 billion on the US consumer credit market, also due to insolvent credit card loans.
However, it is still too early to panic.
There are still very few unpaid bills and unable to pay.
According to the rating agency Moody’s, the third quarter’s insolvency rate of 3.89 percent was almost a whole percentage point below the average.
The deteriorating rates can be explained in part by technical reasons.
A change in the U.S. Personal Bankruptcy Laws of 2005 has led to a sharp decline in the number of bankruptcies, making a large part of the credit card losses; the number of reports (and thus the number of amortizations) would therefore rise regardless of whether the general conditions for lenders have deteriorated.
The industry also shows a good repayment rate, showing how much consumers pay off their debts per month.
And trust in securities secured by credit cards is solid, despite paralysis in other corners of structured finance.
Dennis Moroney of the research firm TowerGroup predicts that their 2007 emissions will be 25% higher than last year.
There are definitely direct pathways to spread the infection between the underlying mortgage crisis and the credit card market: when real estate loans dry out, consumers are more likely to become indebted through credit cards.
Credit card issuers, however, look at cash flow rather than the values of guaranteed items, so falling home prices may not necessarily mean a change in the credibility of lenders.
They can even be advantageous for lenders.
Consumers’ motivation to repay mortgages decreases when the value of their assets drops below the value of the loan; as a result, the debt on the cards moves up the list of priorities to repay.
Card issuers can also react faster and more flexibly to more tumultuous conditions than mortgage providers by changing interest rates or debt limits.
This should theoretically reduce the risks of rapid changes in the prices of guaranteed items.
“It doesn’t happen that one beautiful morning we’ll just rethink all the loans,” says Gary Perlin, chief financial officer at Capital One.
Even though the risk of an explosion in the style of underlying mortgages is low, the danger of gradual weakening is far more real.
If lower home prices and debt cuts push America into recession, the credit card industry will face a darker future.
Be careful of the backflies.
British Bankers Admit Guilt in Enron Case
Three British bankers who were supposed to be tried for their roles in a fraud linked to former financial chief Enron Andrew Fastow on Wednesday changed their testimony and admitted guilt.
David Bermingham, Giles Darby and Gary Mulgrew initially denied guilt in seven fraud charges, in which they had joined Fastow in 2000 to participate in financial fraud -- to get rich on account of their employers.
They were due to stand in court in January.
However, during a trial before U.S. District Judge Ewing Werlein Jr., each admitted to one fraud.
The case of these three former managers of Greenwich NatWest, a division of the Royal Bank of Scotland Group PLC, has been on the front page for two years, which lasted the issuance procedure.
In the United States, their case is one of the unclosed parts of the investigation launched after Enron’s collapse in 2001.
The charges raised against them in 2002 made Mr. Fastow aware that he was the target of the government’s investigation into Enron’s collapse.
The prosecution against the bankers -- who earned the nickname of the "NatWest Troika" -- claims that in 2000 they came to Houston to summon the scam together with Fastow and his former chief affiliate Michael Kopper.
Greenwich NatWest invested in Enron’s affiliate branch controlled by Fastow, who was the architect of a bunch of enron scams that pushed Enron into a spiral of bankruptcy.
At the beginning of 2002, the bank valued its stake in this branch at zero, but our three British knew it actually had a considerable value.
The company under Kopper’s control bought the bank’s stake in this branch for $1 million.
The accused bankers paid Kopper $250,000 for a stake in the company.
According to the indictment, Fastow misleadingly informed Enron that the energy company would pay $20 million for its stake in the Greenwich Branch of NatWest.
But those 20 million actually went to those British bankers, Fastow and others.
The bankers received 7.3 million dollars, while Fastow, Kopper and others received approximately 12.3 million dollars.
In January 2004, Fastow admitted guilt in two conspiracy cases for his role in the Enron collapse.
The British trio was arrested three months later.
Fastow is currently serving a six-year sentence in a federal prison in Louisiana.
Kopper is serving three years and one month in a facility in Texarkana.
The three British were released on bail of $1 million, ordering them to remain in the United States for the upcoming trial.
Enron, once the country’s seventh largest company, went bankrupt in December 2001 after years of accounting tricks made it impossible to hide billions of debts or report failed speculations as profitable.
The collapse lost thousands of jobs, more than $60 billion in market value and more than $2 billion in pension insurance.
Enron founder Kenneth Lay and former chief executive Jeffrey Skilling were convicted last year for their roles in the company’s collapse.
Skilling is serving more than twenty-four years in prison.
Lay’s convictions for conspiracy, fraud and other charges were deleted after he died of heart disease last year.
