The hope that the Fed will lower interest rates leads to strengthening global exchanges
Stock prices on both sides of the Atlantic jumped yesterday after market hopes that the Federal Bank will try to soothe lending conditions by further lowering interest rates were reinforced by reassuring statements by the vice president of the U.S. Central Bank.
The stock markets jumped in London, New York and across Europe after Donald Kohn, second behind Ben Bernanke, the Fed’s chairman, said that in response to the continuing pressure on the financial markets, managers must be “flexible and pragmatic.”
As part of an apparent effort to calm the irritated markets amid signs of a resurgent credit burden, Mr. Kohn said the recent upswing “partially reversed some improvements in market functioning at the end of September and in October.”
He also said that if the increased instability persists, the possibility of further deterioration of the financial conditions of households and will increase.
Investors see these statements as a signal that the Fed is ready to deliver additional fresh donations of capital to the U.S. markets, and possibly further cuts in interest rates to stabilize credit conditions.
These notes also helped calm Wall Street amid further bad news on the U.S. economy, as apartment sales recorded record low figures in October.
The consequences of the financial turmoil were underlined by the announcement by investment bank Bear Stearns that it would cut 650 jobs, or 4% of its global workforce, as part of cutting costs to compensate for the heavy losses caused by the unsuccessful betting on providing inferior housing loans in America.
Only 20 of these jobs are expected to be shut down in London, where the bank employs 1,500 people.
In New York, the Dow Jones Industrial Index grew by 331 points, or 2.55 percent, and closed to 13.289.40, while the more used S&P 500 index strengthened by 2.65 percent.
The London FTSE 100 index boosted by 165.5 points, or 2.7 percent, and closed to 6.306.2, with the value of British blue-chips rising by more than £39 billion.
The German Dax index increased by 2.6 percent and the French CAC40 increased by 2.3 percent.
Some time ago, credit tensions on the markets showed full force after the European Central Bank’s three-month money packages were auctioned to European commercial banks at a rate of 4.7%, the highest since April 2001.
The pressure on the Bank of England to follow the Fed and the ECB and release over-the-counter money to London’s money markets has increased with the three-month British interbank lending rate “Libor” rising after uninterrupted growth since November 12 to its highest since the end of September – 6.59 percent.
