Venus is Earth’s twin.
Despite its life-hostile atmosphere, Venus is more similar to Earth than previously thought.The European spacecraft Venus Express on Venus has recorded phenomena that appear on Earth in the winter: lightning in the atmosphere and winds on the poles.
For three decades, scientists have suspected that Venus is flashing.
Now the European Venus Express spacecraft has brought evidence – it has captured electromagnetic waves on the edge of the atmosphere. On Venus lightning flies from cloud to cloud at an altitude of about 56 kilometers, wrote in the scientific magazine Nature Christopher Russel of the University of California in Los Angeles.
According to a well-known theory of the formation of primordial matter, life could have arisen on Earth thanks to lightning. storms are said to have triggered reactions in the oceans that led to the formation of amino acids, the basic stones of life.
"If life ever existed there, it must have been a very long time ago," explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institute in Washington.
The atmosphere on Venus is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, and sometimes there are temperatures around 500 degrees Celsius.
“Venus may be a hellish twin of Earth, but it’s a twin,” Russell said.
Why Venus, which is so similar in mass and size to Earth, began to evolve completely differently, is the fundamental question of the ESA mission.
Since no spacecraft has been sent exclusively for the purpose of studying Venus since the early 1990s, the launch of the Venus Express in November 2005 was a milestone in the exploration of the planet.
According to the scientists, the latest results of the research, which came in several articles in the journal Nature, not only emphasized the uniqueness of Venus in the solar system.
“They also showed that our neighboring planet is more similar to Earth than previously thought,” Esa said.
In addition to the already known windstorms on the North Pole, scientists have found a cloudy windstorm on the South Pole that rotates much faster.
This phenomenon resembles air currents in the Earth’s northern hemisphere, writes a research team led by Guiseppe Piccioni of the Italian Institute of Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second innermost planet in our solar system has almost the same mass as Earth and is almost as large with a diameter of 12,100 km.
This planet, known as the Dawn or Evening, orbits the Sun in about 225 days.
A day on Venus lasts 243 days on Earth.
Despite the fact that Venus has a surface temperature of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, it does not resemble Earth, scientists believe that the two planets were formed under very similar conditions.
