This is not Warhol’s box.
Whoever combines the terms Sweden and wooden boxes does not think of Andy Warhol, but of Ikea.
Or yes ?
The wooden boxes currently manufactured in Sweden throw dark shadows on the list of Warhol’s works.
Most of his listed ninety-four "Brillo boxes" of the Stockholm type are counterfeit.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" a few months ago raised doubts about the authenticity of Warhol's 1968 "Brillo boxes", an internal research by the Moderna Museet Museum in Stockholm comes with a result that brought disappointment; the six "Brillo boxes" that in 1995 were donated to the Museum Moderna Museet by its former director Pontus Hultén are copies - as are most of the other "Brillo boxes" of the Stockholm type that are in circulation on the international art market.
The preceding events are a messy, confusing chain of artistic and curator events.
Warhol made his first Brillo boxes in New York in 1964, painting wooden boxes, which were based on the red-and-white design of Brillo soap powder paper boxes.
The exhibition of his works at the Moderna Museet in 1968 showed - with Warhol's permission - hundreds of Brillo carton boxes. These did not come (for financial reasons) from Warhol, but were delivered directly from the Brillo factory.
It was not about works of art, but about their subjects, just exhibition pieces.
Warhol apparently also gave permission in 1968 to manufacture several wooden Brillo bins in Sweden, but these are not exhibited at the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses at the time now talk about fifteen boxes that rightly entered the history of art and auction as authorized originals - "Andy Warhol's Brillo Boxes" with the designation Type Stockholm.
Some of them were auctioned for more than $100,000.
The problem now lies in the fact that the legendary director of the museum, Pontus Hultén, later falsely claimed that in 1968 about a hundred bits were manufactured and exhibited in Sweden, which Warhol then left to him.
In fact, 105 Hultén barrels were produced in Malmö for the exhibition in St. Petersburg only in 1990.
At that time, Warhol was three years after his death.
Lars Byström, chief conservationist at Moderna Museet, explored, in addition to the six Brillo boxes owned by the museum, also three Brillo boxes from a Swedish private collection, two of which were made in Sweden in 1968, and after their plywood plates were painted with the basic color and brown, they were painted with oil-white by the brush.
On the contrary, from the structure of copies from 1990 it turned out that the paint was applied directly to the cartridge plate by a painting roll without the prior basic coating - in addition, it is an acrylic paint and not an oil paint.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from Warhol's official Brillo box list," said Lars Nittve, director of Moderna Museet: "If the Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board in New York does not come to other conclusions, Moderna Museet will have to classify six boxes from its exhibition collections as "exhibition material - copies."
In July, the Authentication Board announced that it would deal with these “main charges” raised in the case of soap powder boxes.
Until now, the organization has remained silent.
